CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand (AP) — The Auckland-based Blues hung on to beat the 14-man Crusaders 27-23 in a match between the top-ranked New Zealand teams in Super Rugby Pacific on Friday, claiming their first win in Christchurch in 18 years.In the other game Friday, the Queensland Reds won their third match in a row after beating the Melbourne Rebels 36-32.The Crusaders lost lock and captain Scott Barrett to a red card in the 46th minute when they were trailing 17-10. With center David Havili already in the sin bin, they were down to 13 men and conceded a try which gave the Blues a 24-10 lead.But the Crusaders rallied with two second-half tries to winger Sevu Reece to cut the Blues’ lead to four points and ended the match on attack. A courageous try-saving tackle by Blues captain Dalton Papalii and center Rieko Ioane on Crusaders lock Dominic Gardiner in the 78th minute allowed the Blues to clinch a long-awaited win.ADVERTISEMENTGardiner was put into space on the right flank and seemed to have the goal line at his mercy but Papalii, dazed from a previous tackle, got up and with Ioane’s help forced him into touch.RugbyBlues, Reds hang on to win Super Rugby Pacific matchesBrumbies, Reds coaches in Wallabies coaching spotlightHurricanes beat Moana Pasifika 53-12 in Super Rugby PacificSlipper posts 150 games, Brumbies stay on top in Super Rugby“I don’t really have the words. For me it was quite emotional out there in those last 10 minutes,” Papalii said. “The boys just dug deep and I couldn’t have asked any more of my lads in coming down here and doing the job.”In the contest between All Blacks flyhaves, Beauden Barrett for the Blues had the upper hand early over Richie Mo’unga for the Crusaders and created two first-half tries.Fullback Will Jordan scored the first try of the match for the Crusaders from a dominant scrum, combining with Reece who put him into space.But Barrett broke the Crusaders’ inside defense in the 21st minute to make a try for scrumhalf Finlay Christie and sparked a short-side movement which led to a try to Papali’i in the 31st.With a two-man advantage, Blues hooker Kurt Eklund scored a try from a lineout drive in the 47th to put his team ahead by 14 points.At one stage trailing by 14 points at Melbourne, the Rebels took the lead for the first time in the 63rd minute, edging ahead 25-24 after Matt Toomua converted a much-deserved try from lock Matt Philip.But the Reds then scored twice within two minutes to take control of the match. Prop Taniela Tupou dived across the line in the 66th minute and Josh Flook ran onto a long ball after a break by Fraser McReight to score. ___More AP rugby: https://apnews.com/hub/rugby and https://twitter.com/AP_Sports